{"id":14881462,"mediaExerciseId":"4e70aa5f-c99f-44fc-a7c1-6ced0f27fb1b","exerciseName":"10","chapterName":"14","chapterTitle":"Cost of Capital","groupId":612388,"groupTitle":"Questions and Problems","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":489,"solutions":[{"id":5982772,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"First, we have to find out the after-tax cost of debt which we denote with $AD$, where the cost of debt $CD$ is $6\\%$ and the tax rate $TR$ is $21\\%$\n\n$$\\begin{align*}\nAD&=CD \\times (1-TR)\\\\[7pt]\n&=6\\% \\times (1-21\\%)\\\\[7pt]\n&=0.06 \\times (1-0.21)\\\\[7pt]\n&=0.06 \\times 0.79\\\\[7pt]\n&=0.0474\\\\[7pt]\n&=4.74\\%\n\\end{align*}$$\n\nTherefore, the after tax cost of debt is $\\boxed{4.74\\%}$","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"Now, let's find out the weighted average cost of capital which we denote with $WA$, where the cost of equity $CE$ is $11\\%$, rate of equity $R$ is $1$, the debt of equity ratio $DE$ is $55\\%$ and the after-tax cost of debt $AD$ is $4.74\\%$\n\n$$\\begin{align*}\nWA&=\\biggl(CE \\times \\frac{R}{1+DE}\\biggl) + \\biggl(AD \\times  \\frac{DE}{1+DE}\\biggl)\\\\[12pt]\n&=\\biggl(11\\% \\times \\frac{1}{1+55\\%}\\biggl) + \\biggl(4.74\\% \\times  \\frac{55\\%}{1+55\\%}\\biggl)\\\\[12pt]\n&=\\biggl(0.11 \\times \\frac{1}{1+0.55}\\biggl) + \\biggl(0.0474 \\times  \\frac{0.55}{1+0.55}\\biggl)\\\\[12pt]\n&=\\biggl(0.11 \\times \\frac{1}{1.55}\\biggl) + \\biggl(0.0474 \\times  \\frac{0.55}{1.55}\\biggl)\\\\[12pt]\n&=\\biggl(0.11 \\times 0.645\\biggl) + \\biggl(0.0474 \\times  0.354\\biggl)\\\\[12pt]\n&=0.0709+0.0167\\\\[7pt]\n&=0.0876\\\\[7pt]\n&=8.76\\%\n\\end{align*}$$\n\nTherefore, the weighted average cost of capital is $\\boxed{8.76\\%}$","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"c